#X text 703 93 The [shaper~] object has already been introduced as a convenient object for waveshaping. It automatically wraps the audio input and does everything the patch to the left is doing! It also has a DC filter and everything. The only difference is that it uses another interpolation method (something we'll see later in sampling)., f 48;
#X obj 55 355 graph~;
#X text 296 27 Now we'll get back to working with tables as transfer functions and use "sinesum" e "cosinesum" to generate wavetables. Not that these waveforms are particularly pertinent to waveshaping \, but what's stopping us? To the left we have a plain vanilla patch \, with every necessary step to implement a waveshaper properly \, with guard points and everything.., f 53;
#X text 703 217 The [shaper~] object is also good for chebyshev functions as we'll see next., f 48;
